And there's a, there's a well-known apologist, you probably are familiar with Greg Cocle, who wrote a book called Tactics, and he calls us the, he actually has it as one of his tactics.

18:15.958 --> 18:19.701
He calls it the Colombo tactic, where you just ask questions, you know, you believe that?

18:19.741 --> 18:20.382
Why do you believe that?

18:20.522 --> 18:28.690
You know, and just, you know, kind of go why, why, why, why, and, and a few whys in, it all breaks down, you know?

18:29.186 --> 18:51.092
Um, so that's, that's one thing you can do, but it's, it's, man, that's you're talking about, I think in, in our culture where we were used to this feeling of massive influence because we have hundreds of followers or thousands of followers and we feel like we can, you know, we can get more of the message out there if we tweet it or, or share it on social media.

18:51.112 --> 18:56.338
Um, doing the legwork of relationship one on one with one person.

18:56.930 --> 19:02.837
um, over a long period of time is seems so daunting and seems like such a lot of work.

19:03.538 --> 19:20.598
You know, one, one additional barrier in this that could show up in this situation is even building a relationship might be difficult without you ascending to their worldview.

19:21.900 --> 19:22.160
Right.

19:22.180 --> 19:26.866
Like I could see it very easily be something where it's like,

19:27.074 --> 19:28.395
I cannot be your friend.

19:28.435 --> 19:32.240
I'm not going to spend time with a white supremacist.

19:33.381 --> 19:42.511
If you don't assent to your own whiteness and how you're complicit in all this, then I'm going to cancel you for my life, so to speak.

19:42.831 --> 19:56.626
That's the poison of this movement, is that it even inhibits the ability to form trusting relationships so that you can share the gospel.

19:56.706 --> 20:02.072
I, first of all, I think your second, the second question you brought up is way more difficult to answer than your first.

20:02.372 --> 20:12.483
I think it's gonna be the same as talking to anyone else about the gospel because they're so outside of what we believe.

20:13.184 --> 20:21.593
There's a million reasons when you're talking to somebody who doesn't believe in Jesus, why they shouldn't be friends with you or why a relationship would be difficult.

20:22.514 --> 20:26.098
And I think honestly, a lot of this breaks down

20:26.498 --> 20:29.582
outside of media intermediaries.

20:29.702 --> 20:29.963
Yes.

20:30.624 --> 20:32.026
You get face to face and people.

20:32.066 --> 20:39.135
When you get face to face with somebody who believes this, it is impossible for them not to see you as another human.

20:40.297 --> 20:48.027
And I think when you're face to face with somebody, it's a very, I think it's something on the surface that breaks down really quickly.

20:48.408 --> 20:48.949
It's a good way.

20:48.969 --> 20:55.858
And I think you can come to agreement on things you have in common a lot faster than you can over Twitter or Facebook.

20:56.098 --> 21:13.918
and TikTok and Instagram, I think honestly part of the issue with this is that it's so easy to shout into the wind and dehumanize other people and classify them by race, by privilege, by what they believe.

21:14.158 --> 21:21.166
And then when you're actually sitting down with somebody, having a meal, having a drink, all that kind of breaks down and goes away.

21:21.967 --> 21:23.048
That's a really good point, Sam.

21:23.168 --> 21:25.010
I've noticed that

21:25.090 --> 21:34.704
in my own life, even when you spend a lot of time on social media and you see all of the, you know, the going back and forth, you can walk out, you know, you can just go to the store or whatever.

21:34.864 --> 21:44.198
And you, you almost assume that the real world is going to be everything that you've been hearing and just the animosity and the anger and the hatred and stuff.

21:44.799 --> 21:52.290
And then like, you see people treat each other like courteously and like, you know, like, yep, you realize, oh, people are, there's, there's still humans out there, right?

21:52.310 --> 21:52.691
Yeah.

21:52.711 --> 21:54.994
So I think that's a very good point that you can

21:55.106 --> 22:04.278
Once you get face to face, a lot of that facade, that armor that people have built up melts away, not in every case.

22:04.498 --> 22:07.842
I'm sure there's some real die hard, but that's a really good point.

22:08.003 --> 22:08.443
I like that.

22:09.204 --> 22:10.366
Are you experiencing that?

22:11.147 --> 22:13.670
I mean, are you, are you, you have certain people in mind?

22:13.710 --> 22:18.937
No, this is actually, this is a question, we've been talking about it with, with our college and career group.

22:19.978 --> 22:22.021
Um, how to, how to just navigate this.

22:22.642 --> 22:22.962
Um,

22:23.330 --> 22:25.313
And that's one question that come up.

22:25.353 --> 22:30.901
It's like, how do we, how do we witness when someone looks at you and says, Christian idea is the problem.

22:32.063 --> 22:32.664
I like the same.

22:32.684 --> 22:38.793
I like your point to of of asking questions and listening.

22:39.394 --> 22:47.666
And I think one reason why that's particularly going to be effective in this case is because shutting up and listening is like one of the creeds.

22:47.938 --> 22:51.982
that, you know, like, like, don't don't speak.

22:52.102 --> 22:56.106
You know, if you get really angry and riled, that's just, you're hiding your guilt.

22:56.726 --> 22:56.846
Yeah.

22:56.866 --> 22:58.628
You know, you're hiding your own embarrassment.

22:58.668 --> 22:59.769
So that's why you get riled.

23:00.169 --> 23:01.471
So you just need to be quiet and listen.

23:01.491 --> 23:02.672
White, white fragility.

23:02.712 --> 23:03.292
Right.

23:03.773 --> 23:11.020
And I think the tendency for us, when we hear that, we're like, no, I'm going to get riled just to, you know, because you told me I can't, right.

23:12.321 --> 23:17.906
But even before all of this, we as Christians, that's, that's how we're called to act.

23:18.018 --> 23:19.499
to act with gentleness and respect.

23:20.020 --> 23:23.483
And just because of this new movement, it doesn't change that reality.

23:23.944 --> 23:25.105
Quick to hear slow to speak.

23:25.405 --> 23:25.886
Exactly.

23:25.966 --> 23:27.768
It says right in the Bible, you know?

23:27.868 --> 23:33.974
Yeah, like, it's like, you know what, I just want to, I want to fully and truly understand your belief.

23:34.734 --> 23:37.737
Before I tear it to pieces.

23:37.757 --> 23:39.980
All right, oh, it was a big back flip.

23:40.820 --> 23:43.003
It's the old bait and switch, you know?

23:43.023 --> 23:43.283
That's right.

23:43.303 --> 23:44.244
Yeah.

23:44.264 --> 23:46.546
Well, I think in an advantage too is,

23:46.754 --> 23:51.702
as opposed to like, you know, just straight up atheism where there's no morality.

23:52.143 --> 23:53.946
There's this pity, listen, difference.

23:54.467 --> 23:59.736
These people have some sense of like there needs to be justice.

24:00.097 --> 24:00.377
Yes.

24:00.598 --> 24:01.419
It needs to be equity.

24:01.740 --> 24:05.426
And there's a lot of like good things that are twisted and

24:05.570 --> 24:06.411
misplaced.

24:06.691 --> 24:17.423
And that's what postmodernism and critical race theory came from, was it was a reaction to the enlightenment and the modernist thinking that led to things like eugenics and scientific racism.

24:17.443 --> 24:21.747
So they're trying to assign value to a human being, except without God.

24:21.807 --> 24:26.913
So it's massive confusion and a lot of error there.

24:27.033 --> 24:31.858
But in a lot of ways, there's a heart behind it that

24:32.834 --> 24:34.877
at its core is something good.

24:35.939 --> 24:39.684
It's a heart that at least realizes there's something horribly wrong.

24:40.225 --> 24:41.607
There's something horribly wrong.

24:41.847 --> 24:48.757
That's a great starting point with those folks is that they look at the world and they see everything that's wrong.

24:49.078 --> 24:51.101
They're super sensitive about everything that's wrong.

24:51.401 --> 25:00.274
What a great way to lead into the realization that we're full of sin and that everything is wrong.

25:00.450 --> 25:02.212
Yeah, a lot of these folks are already there.

25:02.432 --> 25:04.595
So it's a, you know, it's a great starting point.

25:05.716 --> 25:20.393
One, uh, one verse that came to mind with this is, uh, in first Peter two, 12, uh, Peter says, keep your conduct among the Gentiles honorable so that when they speak against you as evil doers, right?

25:20.413 --> 25:28.242
So these are, he's telling these Christians, hey, the people around you are going to look at your works and call you eat.

25:28.418 --> 25:33.084
evil, they're going to call you the oppressor or call you the racist, the villain, the racist, right?

25:33.104 --> 25:41.173
They're going to speak against you as evil doers, but keep your conduct among them honorable, that they may see your good deeds and glorify God on the day of visitation.

25:42.014 --> 25:51.846
And that's just why it's so important for our, our testimony to stay consistent with our message, you know, cause.

25:52.126 --> 25:55.250
And regarding your, um, regarding your kind of second point,

25:55.458 --> 25:57.100
That was like drawing the line.

25:57.120 --> 25:58.561
Where do you draw the line with other believers?

25:58.641 --> 25:59.742
Yeah, that's tough.

26:00.223 --> 26:02.044
You're experiencing some of that now, aren't you, Sam?

26:02.084 --> 26:02.425
Yeah.

26:02.825 --> 26:07.209
And in my experience, you don't get that way by accident.

26:08.210 --> 26:16.959
You either have the presence of the gospel in your life and in the community or the absence of the gospel in your life in the community.

26:17.800 --> 26:24.306
There's a difference between full on heresy, throwing away scripture,

26:24.898 --> 26:39.216
Um, you know, there's a lot of churches that are doing that embracing, um, things that the world embrace wholeheartedly and immaturity as a, as a fellow believer, um, or having a lack of gospel influence.

26:39.236 --> 26:43.381
So I think that one's tough because I don't know.

26:43.401 --> 26:53.394
It depends on whether they're being influenced by their church and their surroundings or they, they truly believe, for instance, that, Hey, the word of God is no longer

26:54.018 --> 27:00.847
I don't consider it an authority anymore, which has been a very popular movement.

27:01.447 --> 27:06.234
It always has been, you know, it's always been around, but it's been in evangelical circles.

27:06.294 --> 27:08.717
It's been a popular movement.

27:08.737 --> 27:11.100
It's been the constant threat scary to the church.

27:11.180 --> 27:11.560
Yeah.

27:11.961 --> 27:13.463
So I don't know.

27:13.483 --> 27:14.444
I think that's a tough one to answer.

27:14.464 --> 27:19.090
I think it's just, is it, are they denying scripture or are they just immature?

27:19.298 --> 27:20.439
and they need to be assembled.

27:20.840 --> 27:40.784
I think a lot of the same principles that we talked about, talking with an unbeliever might apply here too, that you're going to have a lot of Christians that just glom on to whatever the thing is, you know, like, oh yeah, this is obviously this is what we should be doing in this situation because it's what the culture and the media and all my friends are telling, especially Christians, you know, on a college campus, secular college campus that are getting fed this all the time.

27:41.405 --> 27:48.914
And a lot of situations they haven't thought through all the way back to, oh my goodness, this view actually undermines the sufficiency of scripture.

27:49.186 --> 27:52.311
Or this actually compromises the gospel.

27:52.972 --> 27:54.534
I didn't realize that before, right?

27:54.614 --> 28:09.996
So it's a matter of being able to guide them to that without hurting a relationship or labeling wrong motives to their view.

28:10.497 --> 28:14.202
What about fellowship between churches or church organizations?

28:14.463 --> 28:16.626
There's kind of this big

28:16.930 --> 28:22.437
uh, schism, if you will, happening in the Southern Baptist church over critical race theory.

28:22.517 --> 28:25.862
You know, you kind of have the woke churches and the non woke churches fighting right now.

28:26.643 --> 28:33.512
You know, like, do you think this is something to break fellowship, break off fellowship over, um, or not?

28:34.753 --> 28:41.522
It's really funny how in a lot of ways you're seeing the

28:41.666 --> 28:47.594
the fundamentalist, modernist controversy of the 1920s happening in a different way.

28:48.595 --> 28:51.359
History just repeats itself over and over and over again.

28:52.080 --> 28:56.746
And you're almost starting to see a new fundamentalism form.

28:57.888 --> 29:04.276
And often divided along that social involvement.

29:05.117 --> 29:11.506
And what is the mission of the church is a big one.

29:11.874 --> 29:21.669
And I'd say, I mean, my view would be just as back at the 1920s, the original, you know, fundamentalist, modernist controversy.

29:22.410 --> 29:25.816
Fundamentalists were right to stand on where they stood.

29:26.356 --> 29:30.002
Obviously, there were over time things.

29:30.562 --> 29:31.844
got kind of lost.

29:31.864 --> 29:40.737
Yeah, the problem with fundamentalists is that they, you know, they just, that's, yeah, they, they, they took that stand where they needed to back in the 50s and then they just stayed in that combative stance.

29:40.797 --> 29:42.720
It became the, it became the label.

29:43.301 --> 29:43.401
Yeah.

29:43.421 --> 29:44.162
What they're known for.

29:44.182 --> 30:00.146
And so that, you know, they, that's what they, they focused on, but, um, so I, I'd say for today, if, if a, if a church views their mission, their great commission as something other than scripture,

30:00.802 --> 30:03.486
then you really can't partner with them, I don't think.

30:03.506 --> 30:03.706
Right.

30:04.026 --> 30:04.647
Yeah, I'd agree.

30:05.168 --> 30:05.829
Yeah, I'd agree too.

30:06.570 --> 30:07.011
It's sad.

30:07.051 --> 30:13.540
I mean, there's a lot of churches that seem to potentially maybe be going that route.

30:14.321 --> 30:14.561
Right.

30:15.162 --> 30:16.484
Yeah.

30:16.604 --> 30:24.335
And a lot of great pastors and evangelical leaders who I've admired over the years going that route, which is strange.

30:24.355 --> 30:25.797
Yeah.

30:26.137 --> 30:29.682
So what about like you're sitting across from a fellow Christian?

30:30.402 --> 30:34.588
and they say we should defund, we should abolish the police.

30:36.971 --> 30:37.592
Is that an issue?

30:38.192 --> 30:42.098
Then you should be like, should I move together and see what life is actually like when there's no law?

30:42.879 --> 30:46.263
I'd say why do you hate black lives and want them to die, you idiot?

30:47.044 --> 30:50.229
I'm now gonna write a satire piece and make fun of you tomorrow.

30:53.493 --> 30:57.138
So like my question is, would that be a scenario where it's like,

30:57.858 --> 30:58.780
You have a different flaw.

30:58.800 --> 31:01.986
You have a different policy view of what might work.

31:02.146 --> 31:05.452
I fundamentally disagree with you on the effectiveness of that.

31:05.512 --> 31:07.055
I wouldn't separate from them.

31:07.095 --> 31:09.359
No, no, I don't think it definitely should not separate.

31:09.420 --> 31:14.469
But how invested should we be in trying to correct that person?

31:14.549 --> 31:18.757
You don't think the idea of getting rid of the police is a biblical issue?

31:18.937 --> 31:21.522
You don't think the Bible has anything to say about that?

31:21.762 --> 31:26.188
I think if you trace the Bible talk about our authorities, you know, not bearing the sword in vain.

31:26.468 --> 31:31.674
I think if you trace it far back enough, it finds its root in how do you view man?

31:32.035 --> 31:39.524
If man's ultimate problem is sin, then you need something in place to keep sin at bay.

31:40.626 --> 31:41.006
Yeah.

31:41.527 --> 31:50.578
If man's ultimate problem is mental health or circumstances,

31:51.138 --> 31:56.884
or poverty, then, you know, police would seem less necessary.

31:57.024 --> 32:03.951
And I think that's part of the problem that you're seeing is you start from that framework of man isn't sinful.

32:04.091 --> 32:07.214
And so why do we need all of these armed police officers here?

32:07.234 --> 32:14.721
Good thing like what, 75, 80% of poll responders don't agree with defunding the police.

32:14.741 --> 32:17.043
So that's always good to... That's still a horrible number.

32:17.104 --> 32:19.666
Just the thought that there are 20% of people

32:19.778 --> 32:23.303
who actually want to defund and get rid of the police.

32:23.403 --> 32:27.409
I mean, the colossal ignorance.

32:27.469 --> 32:28.831
It doesn't actually mean that.

32:28.851 --> 32:30.653
We just use that to shock you.

32:30.853 --> 32:31.474
Reform it.

32:31.735 --> 32:32.275
Oh my gosh.

32:32.295 --> 32:33.477
It's just a better chant.

32:33.798 --> 32:35.039
That's the tough thing.

32:35.420 --> 32:45.474
That's the thing that I struggle with, because politics is intruded into our lives to such an extent where it's almost impossible to separate it from our Christianity.

32:45.554 --> 32:48.498
I mean, if I'm talking to someone who,

32:48.866 --> 32:59.857
is pro-choice and they're doing it from a standpoint of, I believe this is reproductive justice and this is the most loving thing for the mothers and this is what God wants us to do, this is the gospel.

33:00.558 --> 33:10.128
I am going to forcefully and clearly correct and shoot that down.

33:10.148 --> 33:16.434
I think that the idea of defunding the police is the same because it would result in the same amount of

33:16.962 --> 33:21.226
horrific bloodshed, mass death and injustice.

33:22.207 --> 33:25.891
If we were to get rid of the police, you know, I don't care what your motives are for doing that.

33:26.631 --> 33:38.363
I, as a Christian, cannot stand by whatever your motives are and allow people's lives to be destroyed because of your good, lofty motives.

33:38.503 --> 33:44.049
So you would say in that case, that's not a agree to disagree situation with the Christian.

33:44.509 --> 33:45.010
Absolutely not.

33:45.030 --> 33:45.490
Absolutely not.

33:45.602 --> 33:52.732
Would that be, I'm willing to risk our relationship to... Never.

33:52.772 --> 33:54.113
No, I correct you on this.

33:54.134 --> 33:57.158
I don't think any of this should be a risk of our relationship.

33:57.218 --> 34:05.729
I mean, our love for that other person and our relationship with that other person is... None of this should sever that.

34:05.989 --> 34:15.282
I don't care if the person is extremely pro-choice or doing all kinds of horrible things I disagree with.

34:15.650 --> 34:20.758
I don't see how that is a call to sever a relationship with anybody.

34:21.780 --> 34:25.666
That seems kind of antithetical to what a Christian is called to do as well, right?

34:25.846 --> 34:32.236
But should a preacher talk about defunding the police or why it's wrong over the pulpit?

34:36.563 --> 34:37.785
I think we're approaching that point.

34:37.945 --> 34:43.634
I think we're approaching the point where it may have to be

34:43.746 --> 34:44.287
the case.

34:44.687 --> 34:55.098
They need to feed wisdom to their congregations so that the people in church can discern for themselves.

34:55.118 --> 34:55.758
Know how to think.

34:55.778 --> 34:59.662
It is no preacher's job to tell anybody how to think on any issue.

35:00.263 --> 35:02.445
Besides, here's the word of God.

35:02.925 --> 35:04.587
Here's how God says we should think.

35:05.088 --> 35:07.470
Here's how God says we should love our fellow man.

35:07.530 --> 35:11.314
Here's why believers

35:12.226 --> 35:14.048
You know, many believers think that we shouldn't.

35:14.729 --> 35:18.654
And it's based in fundamental principles of our understanding of mankind and sin.

35:19.495 --> 35:21.378
Here's why some believers think we should.

35:21.418 --> 35:31.190
And, you know, it may be misguided in this certain way, it may be found, you know, whatever the case, they need to be equipping their congregations with wisdom.

35:32.071 --> 35:33.052
And they're not doing that.

35:33.113 --> 35:40.562
They're just cotailing to whatever cultural pressure comes their way and put their little tails between their legs and they

35:41.218 --> 35:52.650
say ancillary like little isms of like, oh, by the way, everyone, I just want to let you know that like this church stands with people across the world.

35:53.271 --> 35:55.013
Now let's get into our song for the day.

35:55.053 --> 35:57.816
And it's just like, that's like all they do.

35:57.836 --> 35:59.538
And I'm like, I don't want that.

36:00.099 --> 36:01.700
So it's so stupid.

36:01.780 --> 36:10.610
And I'm just like, I'm tired of people like just freaking like put your head on the neck on the line and just preach the gospel and just

36:10.786 --> 36:12.748
Here I stand, I can do no other.

36:13.248 --> 36:13.829
Absolutely.

36:14.169 --> 36:18.774
Have some freakin' conviction because no one has any, it's so stupid.

36:19.735 --> 36:21.597
That's gonna be my next sermon series, Sam.

36:21.657 --> 36:22.738
Have some freakin' conviction.

36:22.778 --> 36:24.540
Yeah, believe what you believe.

36:24.880 --> 36:27.223
Make sure and include the word freakin' in that.

36:27.243 --> 36:28.404
That's not that hard.

36:28.424 --> 36:28.904
Yeah, freakin' freakin'.

36:28.924 --> 36:30.406
You gotta have the word freakin'.

36:34.290 --> 36:35.831
I agree, that's good, guys.

36:35.871 --> 36:38.514
It's tough, I mean, it really,

36:38.754 --> 36:42.562
It's becoming harder and harder for a Christian not to talk about this stuff.

36:42.782 --> 37:00.498
The next really scary, sticky question that we probably should not get into right now is, at what point can we say that a Christian cannot be a Democrat?

37:01.410 --> 37:09.906
I'm going to hold my tongue on that because we've always said, you know, it's like, like, keep politics and, and, you know, religious beliefs separate.

37:10.267 --> 37:10.487
Yeah.

37:10.948 --> 37:11.229
I don't know.

37:11.249 --> 37:11.649
Can it create?

37:11.669 --> 37:12.771
Can a Christian be a Nazi?

37:13.292 --> 37:14.174
Right.

37:14.194 --> 37:16.258
You know, can a Christian be a Bolshevik?

37:16.719 --> 37:16.939
Right.

